Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Mumias Sugar, Uchumi Supermarkets

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-06-29T16:11:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-29/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-mumias-sugar-uchumi-supermarkets.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
rose for the fourth day, adding 1.5 percent to 842.98 by the 4
p.m. close in Windhoek, the longest winning streak since May 27.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index dropped for the
third day, falling 0.4 percent to 24,923.64 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the
bourse. Kenya’s All-Share Index gained for a third day,
advancing 0.5 percent to 70.33 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed 0.2 percent to 2,090.69 by the
1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index increased less than 0.2 percent to 1,181.10 by
the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mumias Sugar Co. (MSUG KN), Kenya’s biggest maker of the
sweetener, rose for the first time in six trading sessions,
gaining 10 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 7.15 shillings, on
speculation the 4.7 percent drop in the previous five days was
overdone.  “What you are now seeing is purely bargain-buying,”
George Bodo, an equity strategist at Nairobi-based Apex Africa
Ltd., a brokerage, said in a phone interview today.  Uchumi Supermarkets Ltd. (UCSP KN), Kenya’s only publicly
traded retailer, fell for a fifth day, retreating 45 cents, or
3.9 percent, to 11.05 shillings, the lowest since June 8, on
bets inflation will hurt retail sales after accelerating for an
eighth straight month. The annual inflation rate increased to
14.5 percent in June from 13 percent in May, the  Kenya  National
Bureau of Statistics said in an e-mailed statement today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
